{
  "What is enthalpy (H)?": "",
  "The temperature of a reaction, particularly in the context of enthalpy": "",
  "The kinetic energy of molecules according to widely held views on this topic": "",
  "A thermodynamic quantity equal to the internal energy plus pressure times volume (H = U + PV)": "",
  "The entropy of a system, even when conditions shift significantly": "",
  "Enthalpy (H) is defined as H = U + PV, where U is internal energy, P is pressure, and V is volume. At constant pressure, the change in enthalpy equals the heat transferred.": "",
  "For an exothermic reaction, what is the sign of Delta H?": "",
  "Positive": "",
  "Zero": "",
  "It depends on the temperature": "",
  "Negative": "",
  "For an exothermic reaction, the system releases heat, so the enthalpy of products is lower than reactants, making Delta H negative.": "",
  "What does a coffee-cup calorimeter measure?": "",
  "The activation energy": "",
  "The rate of reaction": "",
  "Heat flow at constant volume": "",
  "Heat flow at constant pressure": "",
  "A coffee-cup calorimeter operates at atmospheric (constant) pressure, so it directly measures the enthalpy change (Delta H) of a reaction.": "",
  "A bomb calorimeter operates at constant:": "",
  "Temperature": "",
  "Pressure": "",
  "Entropy": "",
  "Volume": "",
  "A bomb calorimeter is a sealed, rigid container, so it operates at constant volume and measures the internal energy change (Delta U) rather than Delta H directly.": "",
  "What is the standard enthalpy of formation (Delta Hf) of an element in its standard state?": "",
  "A large negative value": "",
  "Different for each element": "",
  "Zero by definition": "",
  "A large positive value": "",
  "By convention, the standard enthalpy of formation of any element in its most stable form at standard conditions (1 atm, 25 C) is defined as zero.": "",
  "Using standard enthalpies of formation, how is Delta H_rxn calculated?": "",
  "Sum of Delta Hf(products) - Sum of Delta Hf(reactants)": "",
  "Product of Delta Hf(products) x Delta Hf(reactants)": "",
  "Sum of all Delta Hf values": "",
  "Sum of Delta Hf(reactants) - Sum of Delta Hf(products)": "",
  "Delta H_rxn = Sum(n x Delta Hf products) - Sum(n x Delta Hf reactants), where n represents the stoichiometric coefficients.": "",
  "When a reaction is reversed, what happens to Delta H?": "",
  "It stays the same, despite what intuition might": "",
  "It changes sign (positive becomes negative or vice versa)": "",
  "It becomes zero according to widely held views": "",
  "It doubles under most circumstances involving Delta": "",
  "When a reaction is reversed, the sign of Delta H changes. If the forward reaction has Delta H = -100 kJ, the reverse has Delta H = +100 kJ.": "",
  "If the coefficients in a balanced equation are doubled, what happens to Delta H?": "",
  "It changes sign": "",
  "It stays the same": "",
  "It is doubled": "",
  "It is halved": "",
  "Enthalpy is an extensive property; multiplying the stoichiometric coefficients by a factor also multiplies Delta H by the same factor.": "",
  "What type of reaction absorbs heat from the surroundings?": "",
  "Isothermal": "",
  "Adiabatic": "",
  "Exothermic": "",
  "Endothermic": "",
  "An endothermic reaction absorbs heat from the surroundings, resulting in a positive Delta H value.": "",
  "What is the relationship between q_system and q_surroundings in calorimetry?": "",
  "They are unrelated": "",
  "q_system = -q_surroundings": "",
  "q_system + q_surroundings = 1": "",
  "q_system = q_surroundings": "",
  "By conservation of energy, heat lost by the system equals heat gained by the surroundings: q_system = -q_surroundings.": "",
  "What does 'enthalpy change' (Delta H) mean?": "",
  "The heat absorbed or released by a reaction at constant pressure": "",
  "The change in temperature during a reaction": "",
  "The change in equilibrium constant": "",
  "The change in reaction rate": "",
  "The enthalpy change (Delta H) is the heat transferred to or from a system during a reaction at constant pressure, equal to q_p.": "",
  "What does 'calorimetry' mean?": "",
  "The study of calories in food": "",
  "The study of color changes in reactions": "",
  "The experimental measurement of heat changes in chemical or physical processes": "",
  "The measurement of gas volumes": "",
  "Calorimetry is the science of measuring heat transfer during chemical reactions or physical changes using a device called a calorimeter.": "",
  "What does 'standard enthalpy of formation' mean?": "",
  "The enthalpy change when a compound decomposes": "",
  "The enthalpy change when elements in their standard states form one mole of a compound": "",
  "The enthalpy of any reaction at standard conditions": "",
  "The enthalpy of combustion at standard conditions": "",
  "Standard enthalpy of formation (Delta Hf) is the enthalpy change when one mole of a compound is formed from its constituent elements in their standard states.": "",
  "What does 'state function' mean?": "",
  "A property that is always constant": "",
  "A property that depends on the path taken to reach the state": "",
  "A function that describes the state of matter": "",
  "A property that depends only on the current state of the system, not on how it got there": "",
  "A state function depends only on the current state of the system (initial and final conditions), not on the path taken. Enthalpy, internal energy, and entropy are state functions.": "",
  "What does 'standard conditions' mean in thermochemistry?": "",
  "0 degrees C and 1 atm": "",
  "100 degrees C and 1 atm": "",
  "25 degrees C (298 K) and 1 atm with 1 M concentration for solutions": "",
  "Any temperature at 1 atm": "",
  "Standard conditions in thermochemistry are 25 degrees C (298 K), 1 atm pressure, and 1 M concentration for solutions. Note: this differs from STP in gas law problems (0 degrees C, 1 atm).": "",
  "What does 'enthalpy of combustion' mean?": "",
  "The enthalpy of any exothermic reaction": "",
  "The enthalpy change when a substance burns completely in oxygen": "",
  "The enthalpy change when oxygen is produced": "",
  "The heat needed to ignite a substance": "",
  "The enthalpy of combustion is the enthalpy change when one mole of a substance undergoes complete combustion with oxygen under standard conditions. It is always negative.": "",
  "What does 'molar enthalpy' mean?": "",
  "The total enthalpy of all molecules in a sample": "",
  "The enthalpy change per mole of a substance reacted or formed": "",
  "The enthalpy at the melting point": "",
  "The average enthalpy of a mixture": "",
  "Molar enthalpy is the enthalpy change expressed per mole of substance, allowing comparison of heat effects for different quantities of reactants.": "",
  "What does 'calorimeter constant' mean?": "",
  "The temperature of the calorimeter before an experiment": "",
  "A fixed numerical constant used in all calorimetry": "",
  "The heat capacity of the calorimeter itself, measuring how much heat it absorbs per degree of temperature change": "",
  "The specific heat of water": "",
  "The calorimeter constant is the heat capacity of the calorimeter apparatus itself, measured in J/C, which accounts for heat absorbed by the calorimeter components.": "",
  "What does 'enthalpy of neutralization' mean?": "",
  "The enthalpy change when a neutral substance is formed": "",
  "The enthalpy of a pH 7 solution": "",
  "The enthalpy change when ions form a precipitate": "",
  "The enthalpy change when an acid reacts with a base to form water and a salt": "",
  "The enthalpy of neutralization is the enthalpy change when an acid and base react to form one mole of water. For strong acid-strong base reactions, it is approximately -57.1 kJ/mol.": "",
  "What does 'heat of solution' mean?": "",
  "The enthalpy change when a solute dissolves in a solvent": "",
  "The temperature of a solution": "",
  "The heat needed to boil a solution": "",
  "The specific heat of a liquid": "",
  "The heat of solution (enthalpy of solution) is the enthalpy change when a solute dissolves in a solvent; it can be positive (endothermic) or negative (exothermic).": "",
  "A student dissolves 4.0 g of NaOH (MW = 40) in 100 mL of water in a calorimeter and measures a temperature increase of 10.0 degrees C. What is the approximate molar enthalpy of solution?": "",
  "-4.18 kJ/mol": "",
  "-44.5 kJ/mol": "",
  "+44.5 kJ/mol": "",
  "+4.18 kJ/mol": "",
  "q = mcDeltaT = 104 x 4.184 x 10.0 = 4351 J (using approximate total mass of 104 g). Moles NaOH = 4.0/40 = 0.10 mol. Molar Delta H = -4351/0.10 = -43,510 J/mol = -43.5 kJ/mol, approximately -44.5 kJ/mol.": "",
  "A nutritionist burns a 2.0 g sample of a candy bar in a bomb calorimeter containing 1500 g of water. The temperature rises by 3.2 degrees C. The calorimeter constant is 850 J/C. How much energy is in the candy sample?": "",
  "About 45.0 kJ": "",
  "About 22.8 kJ": "",
  "About 10.0 kJ": "",
  "About 20.1 kJ": "",
  "q_water = 1500 x 4.184 x 3.2 = 20,083 J. q_calorimeter = 850 x 3.2 = 2,720 J. Total = 22,803 J = 22.8 kJ.": "",
  "Calculate the standard enthalpy of reaction for: 2C2H6(g) + 7O2(g) -> 4CO2(g) + 6H2O(l). Given: Delta Hf(C2H6) = -84.7, Delta Hf(CO2) = -393.5, Delta Hf(H2O) = -285.8 kJ/mol.": "",
  "+3119.6 kJ": "",
  "-679.4 kJ": "",
  "-1559.8 kJ": "",
  "-3119.6 kJ": "",
  "Delta H = [4(-393.5) + 6(-285.8)] - [2(-84.7) + 7(0)] = [-1574 + (-1714.8)] - [-169.4] = -3288.8 + 169.4 = -3119.4 kJ, approximately -3119.6 kJ.": "",
  "A geothermal power plant extracts heat from underground water at 150 degrees C. If 1000 kg of this water cools to 50 degrees C, how much energy is extracted? (c = 4.184 J/g/C)": "",
  "41,840 kJ": "",
  "418,400 kJ": "",
  "4,184 kJ": "",
  "628,600 kJ": "",
  "q = mcDeltaT = 1,000,000 g x 4.184 x 100 = 418,400,000 J = 418,400 kJ.": "",
  "A student performs a calorimetry experiment but forgets to account for heat absorbed by the calorimeter. How would this affect the calculated Delta H?": "",
  "There would be no effect": "",
